			<article class=3D"post-180642 page type-page status-publish hentry">
			=09
				<h2 class=3D"entry-title" style=3D"display: none;">Tire Pressure Calcul=
ator</h2><span class=3D"vcard" style=3D"display: none;"><span class=3D"fn">=
<a href=3D"https://www.renehersecycles.com/author/admin/" title=3D"Posts by=
 admin" rel=3D"author">admin</a></span></span><span class=3D"updated" style=
=3D"display:none">2024-07-12T11:33:01-07:00</span>
				<div class=3D"page-content">
				=09
<div class=3D"wp-block-media-text alignwide is-stacked-on-mobile" style=3D"=
grid-template-columns:60% auto"><figure class=3D"wp-block-media-text__media=
"><img fetchpriority=3D"high" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1024" height=3D"6=
75" src=3D"https://www.renehersecycles.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/Tire_=
Pressure_Paso_Cortes_MR-1024x675.jpg" alt=3D"" class=3D"wp-image-180643 siz=
e-full"></figure><div class=3D"wp-block-media-text__content">
<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Finally a tire pressure calculator based on =
real-road rolling resistance measurements. </h3>



<p class=3D"has-medium-font-size">On real roads=E2=80=94rather than on a st=
eel drum in the lab=E2=80=94supple high-performance tires work best at cons=
iderably lower pressures than most cyclists are used to. Lower pressures ro=
ll as fast or faster, while optimizing comfort and tire grip. They also res=
ult in fewer flat tires: A soft tire often rolls over debris that would pun=
cture a tire inflated to high pressure. Your ideal tire pressure depends on=
 your tire size, your weight (and that of your bike), and your riding style=
 and preferences. </p>
</div></div>



<hr class=3D"wp-block-separator has-css-opacity is-style-wide">



<div class=3D"wp-block-columns is-layout-flex wp-container-core-columns-is-=
layout-9d6595d7 wp-block-columns-is-layout-flex">
<div class=3D"wp-block-column is-layout-flow wp-block-column-is-layout-flow=
" style=3D"flex-basis:40%">
<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Tire Pressure Calculator</h4>



<p>
        <label for=3D"tireWidth">Select your <strong>tire width</strong> (a=
ctual/measured):</label><br>
        <select name=3D"tireWidth" id=3D"tireWidth">
            <option value=3D"25">25 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"26">26 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"27">27 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"28">28 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"29">29 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"30">30 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"31">31 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"32">32 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"33">33 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"34">34 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"35">35 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"36">36 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"37">37 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"38">38 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"39">39 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"40">40 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"41">41 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"42">42 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"43">43 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"44">44 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"45">45 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"46">46 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"47">47 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"48">48 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"49">49 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"50" selected=3D"selected">50 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"51">51 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"52">52 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"53">53 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"54">54 mm</option>
            <option value=3D"55">55 mm</option>
        </select>
    </p>
    <p>
        <label for=3D"combinedWeight">Enter the combined <strong>weight of =
rider and bicycle</strong></label><br>
        <input type=3D"number" min=3D"20" max=3D"200" id=3D"combinedWeight"=
>
        <input type=3D"radio" name=3D"weightUnits" value=3D"kg" id=3D"kg" c=
hecked=3D"checked">
        <label for=3D"kg">Kilograms (kg)</label>
        <input type=3D"radio" name=3D"weightUnits" value=3D"lbs" id=3D"lbs"=
>
        <label for=3D"lbs">Pounds (lbs)</label>
    </p>
    <div>For the lowest rolling resistance, inflate your tires to:</div>
    <div id=3D"message" style=3D"color:red"></div>
    <div>
        Soft: <span id=3D"inflationSoft">
    </span></div>
    <div>
        Firm: <span id=3D"inflationFirm">
    </span></div>
</div>



<div class=3D"wp-block-column is-layout-flow wp-block-column-is-layout-flow=
">
<p>The calculator gives you <strong>two tire pressure recommendations</stro=
ng>. Use the =E2=80=98Soft=E2=80=99 value for gravel, rough pavement, or if=
 you prefer a more comfortable ride. Use the =E2=80=98Firm=E2=80=99 value i=
f you like your bike to have a firm feel. The =E2=80=98Firm=E2=80=99 values=
 also provide a considerable margin of safety if your pressure drops a bit.=
 With the =E2=80=98Soft=E2=80=99 pressure, you are stressing your tire casi=
ng more, and it may wear out faster.</p>



<p>For almost 20 years, we have tested tires in many widths, at many pressu=
res, with many casings and tread patterns=E2=80=94on smooth roads, with a r=
ider on the bike. We=E2=80=99ve found that supple high-performance tires ro=
ll at the same speed at either of these two pressures: soft or firm. Pressu=
res between these two values roll a little slower. On rough surfaces, your =
bike will be faster at the =E2=80=98Soft=E2=80=99 pressure.</p>



<p>These pressure recommendations optimize your bike for speed, but speed i=
sn=E2=80=99t everything. Use these values as starting points to find out wh=
ich pressure feels best for <em>your</em> bike, <em>your</em> terrain and <=
em>your</em> riding style. Also remember that your pump=E2=80=99s gauge may=
 not be accurate. When in doubt, use a tire pressure that feels right and s=
afe to you instead of values provided by the calculator.</p>



<p><strong>Do not exceed the maximum pressure for your tire and/or rim. For=
 tubeless installation, many tires have lower maximum pressures than what=
=E2=80=99s listed on the sidewall. Refer to the specifications of your <str=
ong>tire/rim</strong> manufacturers</strong><strong>.</strong> Maximum pres=
sure for tubeless tires on hookless rims is defined by ETRTO standards: 73 =
psi (5 bar).</p>
</div>
</div>



<hr class=3D"wp-block-separator has-css-opacity is-style-wide">



<div class=3D"wp-block-columns is-layout-flex wp-container-core-columns-is-=
layout-9d6595d7 wp-block-columns-is-layout-flex">
<div class=3D"wp-block-column is-layout-flow wp-block-column-is-layout-flow=
" style=3D"flex-basis:30%"><div class=3D"porto-sicon-box style_1 default-ic=
on flex-wrap"><div class=3D"porto-sicon-header"><h3 class=3D"porto-sicon-ti=
tle" style=3D"">Front v. Rear Pressure</h3></div> <!-- header --><div class=
=3D"porto-sicon-description" style=3D"">Most bikes carry more weight on the=
 rear wheel than the front. However, when you brake hard, almost the entire=
 weight shifts to the front wheel. For that reason, it=E2=80=99s not advisa=
ble to run a lower pressure in the front tire.</div> <!-- description --></=
div><!-- porto-sicon-box --></div>



<div class=3D"wp-block-column is-layout-flow wp-block-column-is-layout-flow=
" style=3D"flex-basis:35%"><div class=3D"porto-sicon-box style_1 default-ic=
on flex-wrap"><div class=3D"porto-sicon-header"><h3 class=3D"porto-sicon-ti=
tle" style=3D"">Even lower pressure?</h3></div> <!-- header --><div class=
=3D"porto-sicon-description" style=3D"">On <strong>very rough</strong> surf=
aces, many riders run even lower pressures than the =E2=80=98Soft=E2=80=99 =
values. This increases speed and comfort. It comes with trade-offs: There i=
s less support for the weight of rider and bike. If these low pressures are=
 used on firm, high-grip surfaces, the tire can collapse under hard corneri=
ng or braking. The tires also flex more at ultra-low pressures, so the side=
walls can wear out faster.</div> <!-- description --></div><!-- porto-sicon=
-box --></div>



<div class=3D"wp-block-column is-layout-flow wp-block-column-is-layout-flow=
" style=3D"flex-basis:29%"><div class=3D"porto-sicon-box style_1 default-ic=
on flex-wrap"><div class=3D"porto-sicon-header"><h3 class=3D"porto-sicon-ti=
tle" style=3D"">Don=E2=80=99t sweat it!</h3></div> <!-- header --><div clas=
s=3D"porto-sicon-description" style=3D"">The =E2=80=98right=E2=80=99 pressu=
re will make your bike a little faster and more comfortable, but the differ=
ence isn=E2=80=99t huge. You won=E2=80=99t get dropped by your friends beca=
use you=E2=80=99re running your tires at too high pressures. More important=
 than tire pressure is choosing supple tires that offer both more speed and=
 more comfort than stiff tires.</div> <!-- description --></div><!-- porto-=
sicon-box --></div>
</div>



<div class=3D"wp-block-columns has-background is-layout-flex wp-container-c=
ore-columns-is-layout-9d6595d7 wp-block-columns-is-layout-flex" style=3D"ba=
ckground-color:#f4f4f4">
<div class=3D"wp-block-column is-layout-flow wp-block-column-is-layout-flow=
">
<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Background</h4>



<div class=3D"wp-block-columns is-layout-flex wp-container-core-columns-is-=
layout-9d6595d7 wp-block-columns-is-layout-flex">
<div class=3D"wp-block-column is-layout-flow wp-block-column-is-layout-flow=
">
<p>Lower pressure means less vibration and less energy lost to suspension l=
osses. That makes up for the higher hysteretic losses due to greater deform=
ation of the tire.</p>



<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"h=
ttps://www.renehersecycles.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Pressure_Suspensi=
on_Hysteresis.jpg" alt=3D"" class=3D"wp-image-158483"></figure>
</div>



<div class=3D"wp-block-column is-layout-flow wp-block-column-is-layout-flow=
">
<p>These two factors =E2=80=93 suspension losses and hysteretic losses =E2=
=80=93 do not interact in a linear way, as shown in the conceptual graph on=
 the left. The result: Mid-range pressures actually roll a little slower th=
an either high or low pressures.</p>



<p>Based on <em>Bicycle Quarterly=E2=80=99s </em>tests of rolling resistanc=
e for different tire widths and pressures, together with Frank Berto=E2=80=
=99s measurements of tire drop under different weights, we have established=
 two tire pressure charts. These charts were translated into this Tire Pres=
